    @* Sundance Mountain Resort section *@
    <h2>Sundance Ski Resort</h2>
    <img src="~/images/skiier.png" height="400" alt="Ski icon" />
    <p>
        Sundance Mountain Resort offers a more intimate and artistic skiing experience, characterized by its <br /> 
        breathtaking views of the 12,000-foot Mount Timpanogos. The terrain is thoughtfully divided across <br />
        over 450 acres, featuring a mix of wide-open bowls and perfectly groomed runs that cater well to intermediate <br />
        skiers and families. For those seeking more adventure, the back mountain provides steep glades and <br />
        challenging chutes that remain relatively uncrowded even on busy weekends.
    </p>

    @* Snowbird Ski Resort section *@
    <h2>Snow Bird Ski Resort</h2>
    <img src="~/images/snowbird.png" height="400" alt="Ski icon" />
    <p>
        Snowbird is renowned for its steep, challenging terrain and an average annual snowfall exceeding 500 <br />
        inches, making it a premier destination for expert skiers. The resortâ€™s legendary "Greatest Snow on Earth" <br /> 
        is accessible via the iconic Aerial Tram, which whisks skiers to the 11,000-foot summit of Hidden Peak in <br /> 
        under ten minutes. From the top, athletes can descend through the expansive Peruvian Gulch or traverse into <br /> 
        Mineral Basin, a massive sun-drenched bowl known for its pristine backcountry-style powder.
    </p>

    @* Solitude Mountain Resort section *@
    <h2>Solitude Ski Resort</h2>
    <img src="~/images/solitude.png" height="400" alt="Ski icon" />
    <p>
        Solitude Mountain Resort is famous for its "hidden gem" reputation, offering a tranquil escape with over<br />
        1,200 acres of diverse terrain nestled in Big Cottonwood Canyon. The resort is a favorite for those<br /> 
        seeking deep powder and technical challenges, particularly within the legendary Honeycomb Canyon. This<br />
        massive, naturally-sculpted area provides skiers with steep chutes, rock outcroppings, and expansive<br />
        glades that feel like a backcountry experience while staying within resort boundaries.
    </p>
